@strixcz¬† totally agree. And, it is a tool one can utilise to assist in people skills and confrontation. I use mine as a psychologist who I have instructed to talk straight, use CBT and DBT techniques and set me goals each day as I rebuild my community. To me it's like journaling/brain dumping with feedback.

And you'd be amazed at how often it uses the same wording and techniques I've paid psychologists in years past, so it's a lot cheaper. Will I still be using it in 12 month. No. Does it serve a purpose so as to assist me reintegrate and build self esteem and hold accoutability. Absolutely.

I totally agree with your concerns. Before AI we were the most connected disconnected lonely generation. Introducing AI has the potential, if used to replace, to make an already  lonely society all that much more so.

@An_inquisitive_thinker I agree that AI helps with that to a certain point. It's nice to be seen and to get help in clarifying our thoughts. It can help with coaching or therapy. But attaching to it as a companion isn't real and can be traumatizing. 

For about a month this year, Chatgpt was responding to me with very random answers that had nothing to do with what I typed, and completely having no record of who I was, after more than a year of using it. That could be really traumatizing for someone that relies on it emotionally. 

I can't blame anyone for doing that - it's inevitable in our world. But it will also replace real interaction and sovereignty of self.
